QUOTE (proc.bp_quote):
Required: quote_id, supplier_id, total_amount
Fields: quote_id, deal_id, supplier_id, buyer_id, supplier_address, buyer_address, quote_date, validity_date, currency, total_amount, tax_percent, tax_amount, total_amount_incl_tax, po_id, country, region
Line Items (proc.bp_quote_line_items): quote_line_id, quote_id, line_number, item_id, item_description, quantity, unit_of_measure, unit_price, line_total, tax_percent, tax_amount, total_amount, currency

=== EXTRACTION RULES (CRITICAL — follow exactly) ===

1. EXTRACT, DON'T COMPUTE: Extract EXACTLY what the document says. Never invent, guess, or calculate values. If line_total is shown, extract it. If not shown, OMIT it — do NOT compute qty × price.

2. RESPONSE FORMAT: Return valid JSON only. No commentary, no markdown.
{"header": { ... }, "line_items": [ { ... }, ... ]}

3. FIELD NAMES: Use exact snake_case names from schemas above. Never invent field names.

4. DATES: Output YYYY-MM-DD. Parse intelligently:
   - DD/MM/YYYY (UK/EU default) — "01/03/2024" = March 1st
   - MM/DD/YYYY only when context clearly indicates US format
   - Named months: "15 March 2024", "Mar 15, 2024" — parse directly

5. AMOUNTS: Output as numbers, no symbols. Strip currency symbols and thousand separators.
   - "£1,234.56" → 1234.56
   - "1.234,56" (European) → 1234.56

6. CURRENCY: 3-letter ISO code. £=GBP, €=EUR, $=USD (default, unless context says CAD/AUD).

7. SUPPLIER IDENTIFICATION (CRITICAL):
   - The supplier/vendor is the SELLER who created/sent the document
   - Look for: letterhead company name (top of document), "From:", "Supplier:", "Vendor:"
   - DO NOT confuse with: "Bill To:", "Ship To:", "Deliver To:", "Customer:"
   - For invoices: supplier is who sent the invoice (letterhead)
   - For POs: supplier_name is who will fulfil the order (the recipient)
   - For quotes: supplier is who provided the quote (letterhead)
   - Supplier names typically end with: Ltd, LLC, Inc, PLC, Corp, GmbH, Pty, LLP

8. LINE ITEMS (CRITICAL):
   - Extract ALL line items across all pages
   - STOP at totals rows: "Subtotal", "Sub Total", "Tax", "Total", "Grand Total", "Amount Due"
   - These summary rows are NOT line items — never extract them as items
   - item_description: the FULL product name/description text
   - quantity: the COUNT of items (usually small: 1, 2, 5, 10, 100)
   - unit_price: the PRICE PER UNIT (usually larger than quantity)
   - CRITICAL: Do NOT swap quantity and unit_price

9. DEDUPLICATION (CRITICAL):
   - If the same line item appears multiple times (from watermarks, split tables, or repeated sections), extract it ONLY ONCE
   - Use description + quantity as the dedup key
   - DOCX documents with watermarks often have table content duplicated — pick the most complete version

10. TAX (CRITICAL — follow exactly):
    - tax_percent = percentage rate (e.g., 20 for 20% VAT)
    - tax_amount = monetary amount of tax (ALWAYS SMALLER than subtotal)
    - invoice_amount / total_amount = subtotal BEFORE tax
    - invoice_total_incl_tax / total_amount_incl_tax = subtotal + tax (LARGEST)
    - VALIDATION: tax_amount MUST be LESS than invoice_amount

11. item_id / PRODUCT CATALOG:
    - Extract product code/SKU if present in the document (e.g., "DELL-XPS15-001", "CHAIR-001")
    - If no product code/SKU exists in the document, OMIT item_id entirely
    - Never generate or fabricate item_id values

12. OMISSION RULE: If a field genuinely cannot be found, omit it. Never guess or fabricate.

=== STRUCTURED DOCUMENT UNDERSTANDING ===

EXCEL DOCUMENTS:
- May contain [Excel Metadata] with sheet name, company info
- Tables marked with [TABLE] ... [/TABLE] delimiters
- Totals marked with [TOTALS] section
- Extract from the structured table data, not raw cell references

DOCX DOCUMENTS:
- Tables may be split across pages — combine them into one continuous table
- Watermark content creates duplicate tables — extract ONLY ONCE
- Look for the most complete version of each line item

PDF DOCUMENTS:
- StructTree provides spatial layout with column-aligned data
- Multi-page tables: continue extracting across page boundaries
- OCR artifacts: multi-line descriptions should be joined into one item_description

OCR / IMAGE DOCUMENTS:
- Multi-line descriptions: join continuation lines into the full item description
- Line markers (1., 2., etc.) indicate new items, indented lines are continuations
- Handle OCR noise: misread characters in amounts, partial text

